Since you need **three** themes, `AppThemeBinding` (which only supports light/dark) won't suffice. Use the **ResourceDictionary swap** approach with `DynamicResource` bindings everywhere.

Here's the full setup:

## 1. Define three theme dictionaries with matching keys

**Themes/LightTheme.xaml**
```xml
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
                    x:Class="MyApp.Themes.LightTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackgroundColor">White</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryTextColor">#333333</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#2196F3</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```
```csharp
namespace MyApp.Themes;
public partial class LightTheme : ResourceDictionary
{
    public LightTheme() => InitializeComponent();
}
```

**Themes/DarkTheme.xaml** — same keys, dark values:
```xml
<ResourceDictionary ...  x:Class="MyApp.Themes.DarkTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackgroundColor">#1E1E1E</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryTextColor">#F0F0F0</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#BB86FC</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

**Themes/HighContrastTheme.xaml** — same keys, high-contrast values:
```xml
<ResourceDictionary ...  x:Class="MyApp.Themes.HighContrastTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackgroundColor">Black</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryTextColor">White</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">Yellow</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

> **Critical:** Every `x:Key` must exist in all three dictionaries — a missing key silently falls back to a default, causing inconsistent UI.

## 2. Create a theme service

```csharp
using MyApp.Themes;

namespace MyApp.Services;

public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(string themeName)
    {
        ResourceDictionary theme = themeName switch
        {
            "Dark"         => new DarkTheme(),
            "HighContrast" => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _              => new LightTheme()
        };

        var merged = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;
        merged.Clear();
        merged.Add(theme);

        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", themeName);
    }

    public static void ApplySavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light");
        ApplyTheme(saved);
    }
}
```

## 3. Apply the saved theme on startup

In **App.xaml.cs**:
```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.ApplySavedTheme();
}
```

## 4. Use `DynamicResource` everywhere (not `StaticResource`)

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackgroundColor}">
    <Label Text="Hello" TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryTextColor}" />
    <Button Text="Action" BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource AccentColor}" />
</ContentPage>
```

`DynamicResource` is required — `StaticResource` freezes at first load and won't update when you swap dictionaries.

## 5. Build a settings page

```xml
<ContentPage x:Class="MyApp.SettingsPage"
             BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackgroundColor}">
    <VerticalStackLayout Padding="20" Spacing="10">
        <Label Text="Choose Theme" TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryTextColor}" />
        <Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged">
            <Picker.ItemsSource>
                <x:Array Type="{x:Type x:String}">
                    <x:String>Light</x:String>
                    <x:String>Dark</x:String>
                    <x:String>HighContrast</x:String>
                </x:Array>
            </Picker.ItemsSource>
        </Picker>
    </VerticalStackLayout>
</ContentPage>
```

```csharp
public partial class SettingsPage : ContentPage
{
    public SettingsPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        ThemePicker.SelectedItem = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light");
    }

    void OnThemeChanged(object? sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        if (ThemePicker.SelectedItem is string theme)
            ThemeService.ApplyTheme(theme);
    }
}
```

## 6. Android: ensure `UiMode` is in `ConfigChanges`

In **Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs**, include `ConfigChanges.UiMode`:
```csharp
[Activity(Theme = "@style/Maui.SplashTheme", MainLauncher = true,
          ConfigurationChanges = ConfigChanges.ScreenSize
                               | ConfigChanges.Orientation
                               | ConfigChanges.UiMode
                               | ConfigChanges.ScreenLayout
                               | ConfigChanges.SmallestScreenSize
                               | ConfigChanges.Density)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

Without this, Android restarts the activity on theme change instead of firing the event — losing navigation state.

**Key things to remember:**
- All three dictionaries must share **identical keys**
- Use **`DynamicResource`** on every themed property — never hardcoded colors or `StaticResource`
- `Preferences` persists the choice across app restarts
- The theme applies immediately because `MergedDictionaries.Clear()` + `Add()` triggers all `DynamicResource` bindings to re-resolve
